    "reasoning": "The problem requires finding the smallest positive integer $a$ such that $N$ can be expressed as the sum of 2017 consecutive positive integers starting at $a$, and no other $k > 1$. The sum of $k$ consecutive integers starting at $a$ is $N = \\frac{k}{2}(2a + k - 1)$. For $k = 2017$, this gives $N = 2017(a + 1008)$. The condition that $N$ has no other representations for $k > 1$ implies $N$ must have exactly one non-trivial representation, which corresponds to $N$ having exactly two odd divisors (1 and 2017). Thus, $N = 2^s \\cdot 2017$ for some $s \\geq 1$. To ensure $a > 0$, $2^s > 1008$, so the smallest $s$ is 10 ($2^{10} = 1024$), giving $a = 1024 - 1008 = 16$. Then $d = a - 15 = 1$.\n\nNext, we determine positive integers $n$ such that for all $m$ with $\\gcd(m, n) = 1$, there exists a permutation $\\pi$ with $\\pi(\\pi(k)) \\equiv mk \\pmod{n}$. This requires that every permutation induced by multiplication by $m$ (coprime to $n$) has a square root in the symmetric group. Analysis shows this holds if and only if $n = 1$ or $n \\equiv 2 \\pmod{4}$ (i.e., $n$ is 1 or twice an odd integer). For $n = 1$, the condition is trivial. For $n \\equiv 2 \\pmod{4}$, the cycle structure of multiplicative permutations ensures even counts of even-length cycles, allowing square roots. Other $n$ fail due to odd cycle counts or invalid permutations.",
    "answer": "all positive integers n that are either 1 or congruent to 2 modulo 4"
}
